Below is a basic script that denies access to a website or service. This script will return a 403 Forbidden response to any incoming requests.

### Using Nginx

If you are using Nginx, you can add the following configuration to your `nginx.conf` file to deny access to a specific URL or directory:
```nginx
location /denied {
    return 403;
}
```
Then, restart your Nginx server to apply the changes.

### Using Apache

If you are using Apache, you can add the following code to your `.htaccess` file or the main Apache configuration file to deny access to a specific URL or directory:
```bash
<Files "denied">
    Order deny,allow
    Deny from all
</Files>
```
### Using Python

If you are using a Python web framework like Flask or Django, you can add the following code to your view function to deny access to a specific URL or endpoint:
```python
from flask import abort

@app.route('/denied')
def denied():
    abort(403)
```
### Using Node.js

If you are using a Node.js web framework like Express.js, you can add the following code to your route function to deny access to a specific URL or endpoint:
```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

app.get('/denied', (req, res) => {
    res.status(403).send('Forbidden');
});
```
### Using IIS (Windows)

If you are using IIS (Internet Information Services) on Windows, you can add the following code to your web.config file to deny access to a specific URL or directory:
```xml
<location path="denied">
    <system.web>
        <authorization>
            <deny users="*" />
        </authorization>
    </system.web>
</location>
```
